1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:16,824
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodasa

2
00:00:17,597 --> 00:00:25,611
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa.

3
00:00:26,213 --> 00:00:30,501
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:33,426 --> 00:00:36,191
Well, a few things have happened since we last met, my goodness.

5
00:00:36,832 --> 00:00:42,222
I think it was Harold Wilson said, a week is a long time in politics.

6
00:00:43,518 --> 00:00:52,552
So although it was on the horizon, something was going to happen in Ukraine whenever I don't think anybody imagined what was what actually has eventuated.

7
00:00:52,612 --> 00:01:05,373
Anyway, I just thought I'd clarify or at least to give you my opinion on this business of nonviolence as opposed to pacifism.

8
00:01:06,890 --> 00:01:11,138
So pacifism really is an ideal.

9
00:01:11,498 --> 00:01:29,792
It's coming from some great concept about violence, making it a sort of global total position at its most radical, sort of an absolute pacifist position.

10
00:01:29,772 --> 00:01:32,615
would never take part in any war.

11
00:01:32,736 --> 00:01:38,743
It's normally centered on war, but of course it does spread out to just killing as well.

12
00:01:39,646 --> 00:01:46,855
And the basic position is that the value of human life is such that killing a person deliberately is just simply not on.

13
00:01:48,597 --> 00:01:55,307
Unfortunately, with isms, they do tend not to be in touch with reality as it is.

14
00:01:55,427 --> 00:01:58,311
So you do get types of pacifisms here.

15
00:01:58,409 --> 00:02:04,894
which are a bit more close to reality, you might say.

16
00:02:04,935 --> 00:02:20,868
So you get militant pacifists who will oppose all violence and war, but then you get conditional pacifism, circumstances where war might actually lead to less suffering.

17
00:02:20,889 --> 00:02:27,555
So I think perhaps the Second World War would be one example of that.

18
00:02:28,074 --> 00:02:29,697
to overcome Nazism.

19
00:02:31,118 --> 00:02:36,086
Then there are selective pacifisms that really only to do with weapons of mass destruction.

20
00:02:37,668 --> 00:02:43,556
But normally speaking, when people talk about pacifism, it tends to be in that absolute category.

21
00:02:45,298 --> 00:02:49,805
Now, nonviolence is of a different nature.

22
00:02:49,824 --> 00:02:55,973
One of the things that I think we find hard to understand is that the Buddha was

23
00:02:56,324 --> 00:02:59,108
The society was preliterate.

24
00:02:59,808 --> 00:03:01,050
So there was no writing.

25
00:03:01,170 --> 00:03:08,021
So if you don't have any writing, you really can't think about things in that sort of systematic philosophical way.

26
00:03:08,641 --> 00:03:11,066
So there are no isms during the Buddha's time.

27
00:03:12,448 --> 00:03:23,664
So the Buddha is always grounding himself on actual experience, his personal experience as to, you know, what actually causes suffering and how to get rid of it.

28
00:03:24,455 --> 00:03:34,485
So there's nothing in the literature like philosophy, as we would recognize it, sociology, systems thinking, there just isn't that sort of thing.

29
00:03:34,846 --> 00:03:42,473
Not that there weren't views and opinions, but there weren't these solid isms that we have these days.

30
00:03:44,395 --> 00:03:51,424
So what he's actually teaching is how to be in a world which is

31
00:03:51,961 --> 00:03:57,579
largely driven at the moment anyway by greed, aversion, fear, and delusion.

32
00:03:58,060 --> 00:04:01,752
So it's a very sort of practical approach to the world.

33
00:04:02,777 --> 00:04:09,308
And this practical approach is coming from a sort of wisdom base, a practical wisdom base.

34
00:04:09,729 --> 00:04:13,996
It's coming from his own personal experience and, of course, the good heart.

35
00:04:14,757 --> 00:04:24,312
So what we're getting to is a sort of ethical stand, a way of relating to people and, in fact, all sentient beings.

36
00:04:24,444 --> 00:04:28,790
And these days, you can also add nature.

37
00:04:29,612 --> 00:04:38,963
So when there's no violence in the mind, the mind is never empty in the sense that there's nothing there apart from maybe sleep.

38
00:04:41,045 --> 00:04:48,355
When there's no violence in the mind, when it's in a state of nonviolence, then, of course, empathy and compassion arise quite naturally.

39
00:04:49,456 --> 00:04:50,317
So...

40
00:04:51,343 --> 00:04:54,649
So those two can't exist together.

41
00:04:54,949 --> 00:04:55,511
That's the point.

42
00:04:56,812 --> 00:05:08,672
Now, interestingly enough, in the discourses, when the kings are talking to him and one or two of them go to war, he never advises the kings to get rid of their armies.

43
00:05:09,392 --> 00:05:12,437
He never tells them to stop executing people.

44
00:05:13,158 --> 00:05:18,668
And also certain punishments were delicious punishments.

45
00:05:18,648 --> 00:05:26,860
There was one I remember which was rubbing the convict's head with a conch shell until the bone glistened.

46
00:05:27,502 --> 00:05:28,803
So, I mean, it's amazing.

47
00:05:29,204 --> 00:05:31,148
It's amazing how we can think up of these things.

48
00:05:32,810 --> 00:05:39,100
But there's a point that he never actually, you know, advises kings to get rid of their armies.

49
00:05:40,221 --> 00:05:45,009
So there's some sort of basic understanding that this is the way it is, you know.

50
00:05:46,492 --> 00:05:50,399
But he does, of course, invite them to develop this sense of nonviolence.

51
00:05:53,764 --> 00:06:00,475
So basically, it's about principle rather than going into the details of how you ought to do something.

52
00:06:00,576 --> 00:06:02,560
So he always leaves that to us.

53
00:06:02,899 --> 00:06:08,550
It's up to us to decide what we feel to be ethically good or bad.

54
00:06:09,795 --> 00:06:17,247
Now, this translated in later Buddhism, in later Buddhist cultures, for instance, the samurai.

55
00:06:17,687 --> 00:06:23,677
The samurai was taught or developed himself to kill without any hatred.

56
00:06:24,538 --> 00:06:34,375
And there was one story where a samurai has beaten his opponent and the sword is high about to crash down on his head and he walks away.

57
00:06:34,415 --> 00:06:36,658
And when they ask him, why did he walk away?

58
00:06:36,677 --> 00:06:37,660
He said he was angry.

59
00:06:40,254 --> 00:06:56,185
And you'll also know the martial art of Aikido, which is really based upon the idea that you use the other person's energy to deflect their violence towards you.

60
00:06:59,572 --> 00:07:02,297
Now, there's another interesting thing about the scriptures.

61
00:07:02,564 --> 00:07:21,483
Remember that when the Buddha was born, the Brahmins, one in particular, a sage, came to see him and sort of decided that or saw that he was either going to be a world-conquering monarch or a fully self-awakened being.

62
00:07:22,403 --> 00:07:28,629
And this alter ego of the world-conquering monarch is in the scriptures.

63
00:07:28,649 --> 00:07:30,512
It's the Chakravartin.

64
00:07:30,728 --> 00:07:34,593
And he has this wheel which appears and begins to roll.

65
00:07:34,634 --> 00:07:43,065
And he follows it with his fourfold army, his foot soldiers, his cavalry, his chariots and his elephants.

66
00:07:43,526 --> 00:07:45,829
And wherever it goes, of course, he defeats the enemy.

67
00:07:45,848 --> 00:07:48,372
And at times he's actually invited.

68
00:07:48,413 --> 00:07:51,598
Now, as soon as he takes over, what does he do?

69
00:07:51,658 --> 00:07:55,403
He establishes the five precepts.

70
00:07:55,382 --> 00:08:02,252
And in so doing, everywhere he goes is just a very peaceful and loving place.

71
00:08:02,954 --> 00:08:08,762
And that's a sort of motif that occasionally comes up in the discourses.

72
00:08:09,442 --> 00:08:17,293
And then it gets to a point where one of these Chakravartins doesn't follow the five precepts.

73
00:08:18,276 --> 00:08:24,124
And immediately the society begins to corrupt and all sorts of things happen.

74
00:08:27,665 --> 00:08:33,832
There was one rather interesting thing, one rather interesting occasion was where stealing began.

75
00:08:34,815 --> 00:08:39,701
So the minister told him, well, the person's stealing because they're poor.

76
00:08:40,682 --> 00:08:47,451
So he decided to give this person some wealth, some land, et cetera, so that he had no reason to steal.

77
00:08:48,192 --> 00:08:52,918
And then others thought, if I want more wealth and land, what I've got to do is steal.

78
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:55,022
So stealing happened.

79
00:08:56,706 --> 00:08:58,028
Stealing became common.

80
00:08:58,369 --> 00:09:01,413
And that's when he had to start chopping heads off.

81
00:09:01,433 --> 00:09:02,754
So that's that's the way it goes.

82
00:09:05,078 --> 00:09:12,928
Now, there's also occasion which is which brings about a rule for the bhikkhus, for the monastic life, bhikkhus and the bhikkhunis.

83
00:09:13,730 --> 00:09:17,735
He is obviously the Buddha is obviously given a very.

84
00:09:18,289 --> 00:09:22,765
enthusiastic talk about the repulsiveness of the body.

85
00:09:23,528 --> 00:09:29,008
And of course, the purpose of seeing the repulsiveness of the body is to become non attached to it.

86
00:09:30,153 --> 00:09:40,947
However, the Bhikkhus, the monks seem to have misunderstood this and they went off in the forests and they began to do this contemplation on the disgusting nature of the body.

87
00:09:41,488 --> 00:09:47,635
And they became so disgusted that they started killing themselves and asked other monks to kill them.

88
00:09:48,177 --> 00:09:55,907
And so there's this wonderful story of a monk who's actually just stabbed a monk to death.

89
00:09:56,495 --> 00:09:58,698
to release him from this disgusting body.

90
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:01,543
And he's wiping the blood off the knife.

91
00:10:02,206 --> 00:10:11,363
But when the Buddha hears about this, of course, he must have been in a bit of a shock, really, because his words had been completely misunderstood.

92
00:10:12,004 --> 00:10:13,966
So anyway, he makes up this rule.

93
00:10:14,649 --> 00:10:19,717
Should any bhikkhu intentionally deprive a human being of life,

94
00:10:20,238 --> 00:10:34,179
or search an assassin for him, or praise the advantages of death, or incite to die in this way, dear friend, what use is this wretched, miserable life to you?

95
00:10:34,548 --> 00:10:36,590
death would be better for you than life.

96
00:10:37,331 --> 00:10:51,826
And with such an idea in mind, such a purpose in mind, should in various ways praise the advantages of death and incite them to die, he is also defeated and no longer in communion.

97
00:10:52,586 --> 00:10:55,269
So this is what we know is known as a paragika.

98
00:10:55,370 --> 00:10:59,815
So in other words, he's defeated in the sense that he can no longer be a monk in this lifetime.

99
00:11:00,615 --> 00:11:02,918
And he leaves the order.

100
00:11:05,192 --> 00:11:24,030
Yeah, the people who actually, this rule, of course, doesn't apply to the people who've just been murdering the other bhikkhus, because it's not backdated, right?

101
00:11:24,051 --> 00:11:25,934
It starts from that point onwards.

102
00:11:30,673 --> 00:11:40,426
Now, the other interesting thing about this rule is that the person has to actually be killed or die for it to be a proper parajika, a proper defeat.

103
00:11:41,025 --> 00:11:56,445
So if the person whom he's trying to attempt to die or intentionally trying to kill him but fails to do so, then it's a serious offence, of course, but he's not actually asked to leave the order.

104
00:12:00,947 --> 00:12:05,913
So we've said it's not a philosophy as such.

105
00:12:06,294 --> 00:12:09,399
It's really just practical moral reasoning.

106
00:12:10,200 --> 00:12:12,942
And these two verses come from the Dhammapada.

107
00:12:14,085 --> 00:12:16,969
All tremble at violence, all fear death.

108
00:12:17,568 --> 00:12:24,238
Seeing others as being like yourself, do not kill and cause or cause others to kill.

109
00:12:24,927 --> 00:12:26,609
All tremble at violence.

110
00:12:27,309 --> 00:12:28,652
Life is dear to all.

111
00:12:28,712 --> 00:12:34,922
Seeing others as being like yourself, do not kill or cause others to kill.

112
00:12:36,263 --> 00:12:44,455
So a distinction here has to be made really between force and violence.

113
00:12:44,495 --> 00:12:46,398
And I think this is the crucial bit.

114
00:12:47,158 --> 00:12:49,702
So for instance, if you drop your mobile phone,

115
00:12:51,217 --> 00:13:00,193
You might just, you know, go and pick it up and see if you've broken the screen and then just put it in your pocket.

116
00:13:00,695 --> 00:13:04,121
But on the other hand, you might be quite angry with yourself and fed up with yourself.

117
00:13:04,581 --> 00:13:11,455
And so you go down and there's that extra pressure in the hand of grabbing this mobile phone and stuffing it in your pocket.

118
00:13:11,991 --> 00:13:22,245
So one is non-violence and the other one is, of course, one is the use of just simple force to put what was wrong or what has been happened that is wrong, to put it right.

119
00:13:22,885 --> 00:13:30,416
Whereas violence is the same with some form of anger, hatred, revenge, etc.

120
00:13:33,038 --> 00:13:37,424
So there are arguments to justify armed intervention.

121
00:13:37,961 --> 00:13:42,014
and which would prevent, say, further worse bloodshed.

122
00:13:43,514 --> 00:13:57,490
And in this terrible thing that's happening in Ukraine, if the soldiers are following their duty, this is the Buddha saying, well, you've been given a command.

123
00:13:58,091 --> 00:14:00,274
This is what you've determined to do with your life.

124
00:14:00,936 --> 00:14:12,610
If they try to kill, or in fact, if they kill soldiers and people of the other side, but there isn't any violent hatred in their hearts doing it,

125
00:14:12,590 --> 00:14:20,361
then obviously that would come under non-violence, but it still isn't something that they should be doing.

126
00:14:22,785 --> 00:14:30,538
Now, the Abhidhamma, this later teaching says that you cannot, you can't kill anything.

127
00:14:30,578 --> 00:14:36,148
You can't kill any sentient being without some negativity in the heart.

128
00:14:36,869 --> 00:14:39,592
But as you can see, to actually

129
00:14:40,282 --> 00:14:55,224
try to, you know, if somebody would try to kill somebody with that sense of hatred, revenge, anger, et cetera, that's a far worse place to come from than somebody who is killing in order to defend themselves.

130
00:14:57,086 --> 00:15:00,130
So anyway, these are just some thoughts that I might put to you.

131
00:15:01,793 --> 00:15:05,158
On the news bite that comes out in a couple of weeks,

132
00:15:05,289 --> 00:15:06,993
I shall put a couple of links.

133
00:15:07,013 --> 00:15:17,408
Some of you might already have started seeing it, but it's a very good set of programs on the BBC about this Ukraine disaster.

134
00:15:18,070 --> 00:15:19,633
And it gives you a bit of back history.

135
00:15:20,453 --> 00:15:33,153
And you can begin to see that it's a product, really, of all sorts of reasons that have come to manifest in this terrible war.

136
00:15:37,639 --> 00:15:38,140
Very good.

137
00:15:38,642 --> 00:15:52,745
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your devotion to nonviolence, you will eventually liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

